# ---------------------------------------------------------
# Exercise 2: Estimation of an univariate model
# ---------------------------------------------------------

# Part 1: State the regression equation
# gdp_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1 \cdot surname_i + u_i

# Part 2: using the LM to estimate the coefficients in the model 
# so GDP is Y (dependent) and then surname is X (independent)
model <- lm(gdp ~ surname, data = merged_df )
print(model)

# Interpretation: use in markdown 
# - $\hat \beta_0$ (intercept): This intercept of 10 077 represents the predicted GDP (in million CHF)
# when the share of Müller's and Maier's is 0 in a canton. This figure
# represents a baseline GDP level for the regression.

# - $\hat \beta_1$ : The surname coefficient of 449550 indicates an increase by 1 unit 
# is associated with an increase in gdp of 449550 million CHF. Since here the surname is measured 
# as a proportion of the permanent population, an increase in the surname share by 1 percentage point (e.g from 4% to 5%) would increase predicted
# GDP by 4495.5 million CHF.

# Part 3: Use the estimated model to predict GDP
# Calculate the population-weighted average surname share across Switzerland
avg_surname <- weighted.mean(merged_df$surname, w = merged_df$population, na.rm = TRUE)

# compute predicted GDP using the regression coefficients
predicted_avg_gdp <- as.numeric(model$coefficients[1] + 
                                  model$coefficients[2] * avg_surname)

print(predicted_avg_gdp)

# Explanation of the predicted change:
# Compared to a baseline canton with no Müllers or Maiers, moving to the population-weighted average surname share triggers a predicted increase in GDP of approximately 41,435 million CHF.

